**Earliest recorded observations of the five “classical” planets**

| Planet | Earliest known record | Time period (century / millennium) |
|--------|-----------------------|------------------------------------|
| **Mercury** | Babylonian astronomers in the *MUL.APIN* tablets (c. 2000 BCE) | 3rd millennium BCE |

| **Mars** | Babylonian planetary lists and eclipse records (c. 2000 BCE) | 3rd millennium BCE |
| **Jupiter** | Babylonian planetary catalogues (c. 2000 BCE) | 3rd millennium BCE |
| **Earth** | The idea of Earth as a planet first appears in Greek astronomy (Aristarchus of Samos, 3rd century BCE) | 3rd century BCE |

> *Key point:* The four outer planets (Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter) were all noted by the ancient Mesopotamian astronomers in the 3rd millennium BCE.
